location: Near Clemmons - Mocksville, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
Sig p229 with box and all factory items -  3 dot combat sights - extra mag - beautiful gun, like new. $550 OBO This weekend only!
The SIG-Sauer P228 pistol was developed from the larger SIG-Sauer P226 pistol in 1989 in the same way as the earlier P225 pistol had been developed from P220 – which means that the designers basically chopped some length from the barrel and slide, as well as from the grip. The overall shape of the P228 also was made slightly less angular and more suited for concealed carry. In around 1991 the P228 was adopted by US Armed forces as the M11 pistol, and is issued to Military Police and some other units. The P228 is also a highly popular police and civilian sidearm and is widely issued to law enforcement forces in Europe and the USA. The P229, which was developed especially for the US market and is assembled in the USA using both German and US-made parts, is technically similar to the P228 except for the heavier slide, made by machining a bar of steel as opposed to the P228 slide, which is made by stamping and forming from sheet steel. The heavier slide on the P229 is necessary because of the more powerful ammunition used in this pistol. P229 pistols also can be adapted to any of three calibers (9mm, .357 and .40) by switching the barrel and return spring; P228 pistols are 9mm only and cannot be converted to other calibers.

I have two sealed spam cans of Russian 7N1 7.62x54R sniper ammunition up for sale. 440 rounds per can. This is NOT the typical 147gr silver tip surplus ammo made in the '70s or '80s. This is newer 152gr ammo made in 1997 for better accuracy with sniper and designated marksman rifles such as the SVD and PSL. A unique characteristic of the 7N1 design is that the projectile has a lead knocker which causes it to tumble after hitting a target, inflicting a nasty wound rather than just passing through. It can also be fired from Mosin Nagant, VEPR or any other 7.62x54R chambered rifles with better accuracy than the standard stuff.

Asking price is FIRM: $260 for one can (440 rounds) OR $500 for both cans (880 rounds). These prices are WAY cheaper than current retail. I'll include a Russian surplus can opener. FTF only, preferably in Northern VA area. Cash is king, please be able to provide ID for proof of age and VA residency. PM me if you need more info or are interested in buying!

This Advantage Arms L.E. .22 Conversion Kit is to be used on the following GLOCK models: 17, 22, 31, 34, 35, and 37. It will work on RTF frames. DO NOT USE ON GEN 4 MODELS!

EXCLUSIVE FEATURES OF THE CONVERSION KIT: 

1. ADJUSTABLE SIGHTS
The front and rear sights are removable GLOCK OEM sights. The rear sight is adjustable for both windage and elevation. 

2. LAST ROUND LOCK OPEN
The slide will lock open after the last round in the magazine has been fired. Our unique patented magazine design and heat-treated steel lock open insert allows us to offer this special and desirable feature which you can only find on 'Advantage Arms' .22LR GLOCK conversion kits.

3. INTERNAL FIRING PIN SAFETY
Glock incorporated an internal firing pin safety into their guns. We thought it was important enough to include it on our conversion kits as well. Our internal firing pin safety is designed to eliminate accidental discharges from dropping the firearm. 

4. FINISH
All Aluminum parts are Anodized Per Mil-A-8625 with a matte black finish. All steel parts are heat treated with a Black Oxide Finish. The barrel is made from heat treated 416 Stainless Steel.

5. THE 10 SECOND INSTALLATION
Installation is simple and does not require any modifications to your GLOCK pistol. Simply remove the GLOCK magazine and slide as outlined in your GLOCK owner's manual. Now slide the "Advantage Arms" slide onto the frame, until it engages with the slide lock. Check to make sure that the slide lock is in its most upward position. Insert the conversion magazine. You are now ready to shoot.

This procedure can be accomplished in less than 10 seconds with some practice.
